{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Is Classical Planning?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classical planning is the problem of finding a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "sequence of actions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that transforms an initial state into a state satisfying a goal, given a model of how actions change the world. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "STRIPS"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (Stanford Research Institute Problem Solver, 1971) formalized this as a tuple: initial state, goal condition, and a set of operators each with preconditions and effects. PDDL (Planning Domain Definition Language) is the modern standardized syntax for expressing STRIPS-style problems."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "STRIPS state-space search: initial state transitions through pick-up and stack actions to reach goal state; operator anatomy shows preconditions, add effects, delete effects",
          "title": "STRIPS state-space search and operator anatomy (Blocks World example)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "In agentic AI, classical planning is relevant as the foundation for understanding plan generation. Modern LLM planners implicitly solve the same problem \u2014 they just do it through learned associations rather than explicit search."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "STRIPS Operators and State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A STRIPS state is a set of ground atoms (propositions that are currently true). An operator has three parts: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "preconditions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (atoms that must be true for the action to apply), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "add effects"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (atoms that become true), and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "delete effects"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (atoms that become false):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import frozenset\n\n# A state is a frozenset of ground atoms (string facts)\nState = frozenset[str]\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass Operator:\n    name: str\n    preconditions: frozenset[str]  # must all be true in current state\n    add_effects:   frozenset[str]  # become true after action\n    delete_effects: frozenset[str] # become false after action\n\n    def applicable(self, state: State) -> bool:\n        return self.preconditions <= state\n\n    def apply(self, state: State) -> State:\n        return (state - self.delete_effects) | self.add_effects\n\n# Blocks World operators\nOPERATORS = [\n    Operator(\n        name=\"pick-up(A)\",\n        preconditions=frozenset({\"clear(A)\", \"on(A,table)\", \"hand-empty\"}),\n        add_effects=frozenset({\"holding(A)\"}),\n        delete_effects=frozenset({\"clear(A)\", \"on(A,table)\", \"hand-empty\"}),\n    ),\n    Operator(\n        name=\"stack(A,B)\",\n        preconditions=frozenset({\"holding(A)\", \"clear(B)\"}),\n        add_effects=frozenset({\"on(A,B)\", \"clear(A)\", \"hand-empty\"}),\n        delete_effects=frozenset({\"holding(A)\", \"clear(B)\"}),\n    ),\n]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "applicable()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " method checks whether the current state satisfies all preconditions. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "apply()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " method produces the successor state by removing delete-effect atoms and adding add-effect atoms. This is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "closed-world assumption"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": anything not in the state is false."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forward Search (BFS)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest planner is breadth-first search over the state space: start at the initial state, apply every applicable operator, enqueue successor states, and stop when the goal is satisfied. BFS guarantees the shortest (fewest-action) plan:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import deque\n\ndef bfs_plan(\n    initial: State,\n    goal: State,\n    operators: list[Operator],\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"BFS over the state space; returns action sequence or None.\"\"\"\n    # Each entry: (current_state, path_of_operator_names)\n    queue   = deque([(initial, [])])\n    visited = {initial}\n\n    while queue:\n        state, path = queue.popleft()\n        if goal <= state:         # goal is satisfied (subset check)\n            return path\n        for op in operators:\n            if op.applicable(state):\n                next_state = op.apply(state)\n                if next_state not in visited:\n                    visited.add(next_state)\n                    queue.append((next_state, path + [op.name]))\n    return None  # no plan found\n\n# Example:\nINITIAL = frozenset({\"on(A,table)\", \"on(B,table)\", \"clear(A)\", \"clear(B)\", \"hand-empty\"})\nGOAL    = frozenset({\"on(A,B)\"})\nplan    = bfs_plan(INITIAL, GOAL, OPERATORS)\n# plan -> [\"pick-up(A)\", \"stack(A,B)\"]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BFS is complete (finds a plan if one exists) and optimal (finds the shortest plan). The problem is space: the state space grows exponentially with the number of propositions. For real-world domains with 20+ propositions, BFS is impractical without heuristics."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Heuristic Search with A*"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A* uses a heuristic function "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "h(state)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that estimates the remaining cost to the goal. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "additive heuristic"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (h-add) solves a relaxed version of the problem \u2014 ignoring delete effects \u2014 to produce a fast lower-bound estimate:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def h_add(state: State, goal: State, operators: list[Operator]) -> int:\n    \"\"\"Additive heuristic: relaxed planning graph cost.\n\n    Ignores delete effects (relaxation) and sums up the minimum\n    number of actions needed to achieve each goal atom independently.\n    Admissible lower bound; fast to compute.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Cost table: atom -> min actions to achieve from current state\n    cost: dict[str, int] = {atom: 0 for atom in state}\n    changed = True\n    while changed:\n        changed = False\n        for op in operators:\n            # Relaxed: operator applies if all preconditions are reachable\n            if all(p in cost for p in op.preconditions):\n                op_cost = 1 + max((cost[p] for p in op.preconditions), default=0)\n                for eff in op.add_effects:\n                    if eff not in cost or op_cost < cost[eff]:\n                        cost[eff] = op_cost\n                        changed = True\n    missing = goal - cost.keys()\n    if missing:\n        return float(\"inf\")  # goal is unreachable\n    return sum(cost.get(g, float(\"inf\")) for g in goal)\n\ndef astar_plan(\n    initial: State,\n    goal: State,\n    operators: list[Operator],\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"A* with additive heuristic; optimal for unit-cost operators.\"\"\"\n    import heapq\n    h0 = h_add(initial, goal, operators)\n    # heap: (f, g, state, path)\n    heap = [(h0, 0, initial, [])]\n    best: dict[State, int] = {initial: 0}\n\n    while heap:\n        f, g, state, path = heapq.heappop(heap)\n        if goal <= state:\n            return path\n        for op in operators:\n            if op.applicable(state):\n                ns     = op.apply(state)\n                ng     = g + 1\n                if ns not in best or ng < best[ns]:\n                    best[ns] = ng\n                    h = h_add(ns, goal, operators)\n                    heapq.heappush(heap, (ng + h, ng, ns, path + [op.name]))\n    return None"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The h-add heuristic is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "not admissible"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in general (it can overestimate when goals share preconditions), but it is fast and works well in practice. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "h-max heuristic"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (taking max instead of sum) is admissible but weaker."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using an LLM to Generate STRIPS Problems"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The bridge between natural language and classical planning is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "problem formulation step"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": converting a user's goal description into a STRIPS tuple. An LLM is well-suited to this because it can identify the relevant objects, propose meaningful predicates, and reason about action preconditions and effects:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PDDL_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nYou are given a planning problem in natural language.\nConvert it into a STRIPS-style representation with:\n- initial_state: list of true ground atoms\n- goal: list of atoms that must be true\n- operators: list of {name, preconditions, add_effects, delete_effects}\n\nProblem: {problem}\n\nReturn JSON matching this schema:\n{{\n  \"initial_state\": [\"atom1\", \"atom2\", ...],\n  \"goal\": [\"atom1\", ...],\n  \"operators\": [\n    {{\n      \"name\": \"action_name\",\n      \"preconditions\": [\"atom1\", ...],\n      \"add_effects\": [\"atom1\", ...],\n      \"delete_effects\": [\"atom1\", ...]\n    }}\n  ]\n}}\n\"\"\"\n\ndef nl_to_strips(problem_description: str) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Convert a natural-language problem to STRIPS via LLM.\"\"\"\n    response = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=2048,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": PDDL_PROMPT.format(\n            problem=problem_description\n        )}],\n    )\n    return json.loads(response.content[0].text)\n\ndef solve_nl_problem(problem_description: str) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"End-to-end: NL -> STRIPS -> BFS plan.\"\"\"\n    strips_data = nl_to_strips(problem_description)\n    initial = frozenset(strips_data[\"initial_state\"])\n    goal    = frozenset(strips_data[\"goal\"])\n    ops     = [\n        Operator(\n            name=o[\"name\"],\n            preconditions=frozenset(o[\"preconditions\"]),\n            add_effects=frozenset(o[\"add_effects\"]),\n            delete_effects=frozenset(o[\"delete_effects\"]),\n        )\n        for o in strips_data[\"operators\"]\n    ]\n    return bfs_plan(initial, goal, ops)\n\n# Example:\n# plan = solve_nl_problem(\n#     \"Move block A from the table to block B. B is on the table. \"\n#     \"The robot arm is empty and both blocks are clear.\"\n# )\n# -> [\"pick-up(A)\", \"stack(A,B)\"]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "What the LLM must get right:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " precondition/effect completeness (missing a delete effect causes inconsistent states), and goal reachability (the goal must follow from the initial state via the operators). The BFS planner will return "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "None"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " if the problem is unsolvable \u2014 which is often the signal that the LLM's formulation has a bug."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parametric Operators and Grounding"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical STRIPS domains use parametric operators with variables ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "?X"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "?Y"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") instead of ground operators. Grounding instantiates all combinations of objects for each parameter. In the blocks world with 3 blocks, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "stack(?X,?Y)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " grounds to 9 operators (3\u00d73) including invalid same-block cases:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Parametric operators need grounding over object constants\nOBJECTS = {\"A\", \"B\", \"C\"}  # blocks\n\ndef parametric_operator(name_template: str, **param_bindings) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Substitute parameters in an operator template.\"\"\"\n    result = name_template\n    for param, value in param_bindings.items():\n        result = result.replace(f\"?{param}\", value)\n    return result\n\ndef ground_operators(\n    parametric_ops: list[dict],\n    objects: set[str],\n) -> list[Operator]:\n    \"\"\"Instantiate all valid ground operators from parametric templates.\n\n    A parametric operator uses ?X, ?Y placeholders;\n    this function expands them over all object combinations.\n    Invalid groundings (e.g. stack(A, A)) are filtered by precondition check\n    at search time, not here.\n    \"\"\"\n    from itertools import product\n    ground_ops = []\n    for op in parametric_ops:\n        params = op[\"params\"]  # e.g. [\"?X\", \"?Y\"]\n        for binding in product(objects, repeat=len(params)):\n            sub = dict(zip(params, binding))\n            def substitute(atoms):\n                return frozenset(\n                    a.replace(p, v) for a in atoms for p, v in sub.items()\n                    if True  # apply all substitutions\n                ) if atoms else frozenset()\n            # apply all param substitutions to each atom\n            subbed_pre = frozenset(\n                atom.replace(p, v)\n                for atom in op[\"preconditions\"]\n                for p, v in [(params[i], binding[i]) for i in range(len(params))]\n            )\n            # (simplified: in practice, apply all params to each atom in one pass)\n            name = op[\"name\"]\n            for p, v in zip(params, binding):\n                name = name.replace(p, v)\n            ground_ops.append(Operator(\n                name=name,\n                preconditions=frozenset(\n                    a.replace(params[i], binding[i])\n                    for a in op[\"preconditions\"]\n                    for i in range(len(params))\n                ),\n                add_effects=frozenset(\n                    a.replace(params[i], binding[i])\n                    for a in op[\"add_effects\"]\n                    for i in range(len(params))\n                ),\n                delete_effects=frozenset(\n                    a.replace(params[i], binding[i])\n                    for a in op[\"delete_effects\"]\n                    for i in range(len(params))\n                ),\n            ))\n    return ground_ops"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Note: grounding of 3 blocks yields 9 instances of each 2-parameter operator. For 10 objects this becomes 100 instances per operator \u2014 the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "grounding bottleneck"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " limits classical planners to domains with tens of objects. LLM-based planners sidestep this by working directly with natural-language descriptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
